<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900402-0055</DOCNO><DOCID>900402-0055.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Pearson PLC:   British Publishing Concern's   '89 Pretax Profit Rose 26%</HL><DATE>04/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   U.PSO</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><LP>   Pearson PLC, a British publishing conglomerate that ownsthe Financial Times, reported 1989 pretax profit rose 26% to#250.5 million ($409.7 million) from #198.9 million a yearearlier, helped by gains in all divisions exceptentertainment.   Profit after taxes and minority interests increased 35% to#171.8 million from #126.9 million. Per-share earnings gained20% to 67 pence from 55.7 pence. Sales jumped 22% to #1.45billion from #1.19 billion.</LP><TEXT>   The company recommended a final dividend of 12.5 pence ashare, which would boost the total payout for the year 19% to21.5 pence from 18 pence.   Pearson said the results represented &quot;the best-everprofits for the group,&quot; with record earnings for itspublications, the Financial Times, the Economist and LesEchos, the publishers Addison-Wesley and Longman, financialservices interests and Royal Doulton china unit.   Profit attributable to shareholders was boosted by anextraordinary profit of #104.4 million, mostly from sheddingassets. Net income rose 57% to #276.2 million from theyear-earlier #175.7 million, which included an extraordinarygain of #48.8 million.</TEXT></DOC>